Balanced risk management is promoted by the United States Congress and the Office of Management and Budget. The Information Technology Management Reform Act, the Financial Management Reform Act, The Government Information Security Reform Act, and the follow-on Federal Information Management Act all provide examples of this view. Included in the list of identified activities are change management, resource management, knowledge management, strategic planning, technology assessment, architecture and standards, capital planning, information security, assessment and metrics, acquisition, and operations and maintenance.